ough booking-service for reservation flow.22. Appendix — Key Design DecisionsA. Why JSON Schema for Theme Fields?Schema-driven field definitions mean the editor UI is generated automatically from the theme package — no separate editor config files, no duplication. Adding a new field to a section is one TypeScript object addition and it immediately appears in the editor panel. This also enables automated validation and type safety end-to-end.B. Why JSONB for Section Content?Section content is inherently varied and schema-divergent across section types. Storing it as JSONB gives flexibility without a table-per-section-type explosion. PostgreSQL JSONB offers indexed queries where needed (e.g., find all sections using a specific package ID). The theme schema provides application-level validation before any JSONB write.C. Why One Published Theme Enforced by DB Constraint?The partial unique index (UNIQUE WHERE status = 'published') makes it physically impossible to have two published themes for one tenant — even with concurrent API calls. This removes an entire class of race condition bugs that would be dangerous for live sites.D. Why ISR over Pure SSG or Pure SSR?ISR gives the best balance: pages are statically cached at Cloudflare edge for performance, but automatically regenerate on a timer and can be instantly busted on publish. Pure SSG would require a full rebuild on every publish (slow for agencies with many packages). Pure SSR on every request would be expensive at scale and slower for visitors.E. Why Cloudflare Workers for Domain Routing (Not NGINX)?Cloudflare Workers execute at 200+ edge locations globally in < 1ms. Custom domain routing at the edge means no extra RTT to origin for domain resolution. The KV store lookup is sub-millisecond. An NGINX approach would centralize this routing at the origin, adding latency for all global visitors.